ce:section.ce:para:
CDs were prepared in one step via the facial hydrothermal method. The cassava peel was utilized to synthesize CDs since its chemical composition was lignocellulose, including hemicellulose (32%), lignin (17%), and cellulose (∼10%) [2]. The formation of lignocellulose-derived CDs was proposed through dehydration and depolymerization reactions in a high-temperature aqueous environment. These small molecular fragments resulted from inter- and intra-molecular dehydration and condensation reactions, which produce several kinds of covalent molecules, subsequently participating in polymerization, cross-linking, and carbonization to finally form CDs [4]. The morphology and particle size distribution histogram of CDs were studied using TEM (Fig. 1
                        ). The average particle size of CDs was 3.4 nm and was narrowly distributed between 2 and 6 nm. Fig. 1b reveals a good dispersion of CDs with a lattice space of 0.13 nm. The crystalline structure of CDs was also elucidated by the XRD technique (Fig. 2
                        a). XRD analysis showed a broad peak corresponding to the (002) graphite carbon at 2θ = 19.06°, indicating the amorphous structure [5].

The linear correlation plot of fluorescence enhancement and the concentration of Fe3+ and Hg2+ was elucidated from the fluorescence titration experiments. Fluorescence titration of CDs upon the addition of Hg2+ and Fe3+ in the concentration range of 0−10 mM was explored using the excitation wavelength at 360 nm (Fig. 7
                        a, c). The fluorescence intensity of CDs significantly decreased with the increasing concentrations of Hg2+ and Fe3+ until 1.0 mM. The good linear calibration curve of fluorescence intensity and the concentrations of Fe3+ and Hg2+ were observed in the range of 0−800 μM with y = 5.1699x + 36.036 (R2
                         = 0.9984) and 20−250 μM with y = 14.695x + 106.25 (R2
                         = 0.9965), respectively (Fig. 7b, d). Therefore, the limit of detection (LOD) values based on signal-to-noise (S/N = 3) for Fe3+ and Hg2+ were determined to be 68.0 and 23.9 μM, respectively, which is less than other previous reports (Table 1
                        ). The fluorescence quenching efficiency of CDs for binding Fe3+ and Hg2+ was determined by the Stern-Volmer constant (Ksv) (Fig. S2). Ksv values were 2.4×103 M−1 and 6.3×103 M−1 for Fe3+ and Hg2+ recognition, respectively. Moreover, the Stern-Volmer plot was utilized to identify the static or dynamic quenching process. For the fluorescence quenching of Hg2+ and Fe3+, the linear Stern-Volmer plots were observed in low concentrations, and the nonlinear plots were also observed in high concentrations of these ions. These results suggest that the fluorescence quenching mechanism occurred via static and dynamic quenching processes. Time-dependent fluorescence plots of CDs in the presence of Fe3+ and Hg2+ (1.0 mM) were investigated in deionized water (Fig. 7). The fluorescence emission of CDs was completely quenched within 1 min, suggesting that CDs could be applied as a rapid fluorescent sensor for sensing Fe3+ and Hg2+ (Fig. 8
                        ).
